WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.411 --> 00:00:05.660
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: So anyway.

00:00:05.660 --> 00:00:06.951
Real quick, I'm John Alferness.

00:00:06.951 --> 00:00:09.860
I work here at Google, and
I've been here for a long time.

00:00:09.860 --> 00:00:13.750
But more excitingly is David
Lebovitz, whose here with us

00:00:13.750 --> 00:00:15.369
today.

00:00:15.369 --> 00:00:17.160
I'm really fortunate
to be able to do this,

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:19.410
because David's actually a
really good friend of mine.

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:22.550
My wife and I have known
David since the early days

00:00:22.550 --> 00:00:25.050
where my wife was
a food blogger.

00:00:25.050 --> 00:00:27.910
And David certainly, being one
of the most quintessential food

00:00:27.910 --> 00:00:32.340
bloggers out there, is somebody
that we got to know early on.

00:00:32.340 --> 00:00:36.160
David, for those of
you who don't know,

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:40.720
is just quite an
illuminary in this field.

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:42.890
David worked at Chez
Panisse as the pastry chef

00:00:42.890 --> 00:00:45.720
for about 13 years.

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:47.340
He pivoted then
in the late '90s,

00:00:47.340 --> 00:00:50.910
I think roughly 1999, where
he started writing more,

00:00:50.910 --> 00:00:52.060
starting with blogs.

00:00:52.060 --> 00:00:53.880
And if you, I mean
I know for us,

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:56.660
probably 1999 felt like
blogs were in full swing.

00:00:56.660 --> 00:01:00.910
But David was really one of the
first food bloggers out there,

00:01:00.910 --> 00:01:03.971
and remains one of the most
influential food bloggers

00:01:03.971 --> 00:01:04.970
that we continue to see.

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:07.340
Flood bloggers.

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:09.830
David's written, I don't
know how many books.

00:01:09.830 --> 00:01:11.690
Probably more than
a half dozen or so.

00:01:11.690 --> 00:01:14.000
It's somewhere in
the back pamphlet

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:17.740
of this book, of which I've
used more than a couple

00:01:17.740 --> 00:01:19.654
to actually bang out
some great recipes.

00:01:19.654 --> 00:01:22.070
His ice cream book, if you
haven't bought it and tried it,

00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:23.060
kicks ass.

00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:24.780
It's really, really awesome.

00:01:24.780 --> 00:01:28.220
Anyway, David's now been living
in Paris for the last 10 years

00:01:28.220 --> 00:01:29.690
or so.

00:01:29.690 --> 00:01:32.230
He does tours of Paris,
he's introduced us

00:01:32.230 --> 00:01:35.680
to our favorite chocolates
here in all the world,

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:38.360
and showed us your wonderful
shop, which unfortunately

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:40.087
had a big fire recently.

00:01:40.087 --> 00:01:41.170
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Explosion.

00:01:41.170 --> 00:01:43.045
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
Explosion, and then fire.

00:01:43.045 --> 00:01:44.910
But she's OK, Denise is OK.

00:01:44.910 --> 00:01:47.040
Anyway, David is
here with us today

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:49.167
to answer a few of my questions.

00:01:49.167 --> 00:01:51.500
But then more importantly,
answer all of your questions,

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:54.670
probably ask you guys some
questions too about Google

00:01:54.670 --> 00:01:57.990
and what we can do for David.

00:01:57.990 --> 00:02:01.330
But really, this is just
a huge pleasure for me

00:02:01.330 --> 00:02:02.530
and I think for all of us.

00:02:02.530 --> 00:02:04.890
So let's take a quick
second to welcome David.

00:02:04.890 --> 00:02:06.330
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:06.330 --> 00:02:09.210
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Well, thanks.

00:02:09.210 --> 00:02:11.450
Everybody, I have
friends-- Cindy

00:02:11.450 --> 00:02:13.340
over here, who tested
recipes for the books,

00:02:13.340 --> 00:02:15.097
works at Google for the book.

00:02:15.097 --> 00:02:16.680
But whenever I have
Google [INAUDIBLE]

00:02:16.680 --> 00:02:19.167
they go oh, that's
not my category.

00:02:19.167 --> 00:02:20.750
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
We're really going

00:02:20.750 --> 00:02:22.041
to evading questions at Google.

00:02:22.041 --> 00:02:24.042
So we'll see how good you
are evading questions.

00:02:24.042 --> 00:02:26.416
DAVID LEBOVITZ: As a blogger,
I'm getting better at that.

00:02:26.416 --> 00:02:28.380
Actually, I need to get
some tips on that too.

00:02:28.380 --> 00:02:30.820
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: So let's
do the history little bit.

00:02:30.820 --> 00:02:32.570
I mean, Chez Panisse,
if you ask me,

00:02:32.570 --> 00:02:38.050
is one of, if not the most
quintessential California

00:02:38.050 --> 00:02:39.490
restaurants.

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:42.290
I think it really
changed the pace

00:02:42.290 --> 00:02:45.310
of how Californians
think about food.

00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:47.534
And it just kind of keeps going.

00:02:47.534 --> 00:02:49.700
Anybody who's eaten there
over a long period of time

00:02:49.700 --> 00:02:52.199
knows the consistency that's
there, and the qualities there.

00:02:52.199 --> 00:02:55.950
What was it like working as a
pastry chef at Chez Panisse?

00:02:55.950 --> 00:02:58.200
I know you have all kinds
of great anecdotes to share.

00:02:58.200 --> 00:02:59.847
Maybe you could
just share a couple.

00:02:59.847 --> 00:03:01.930
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Well, I
started there, actually it

00:03:01.930 --> 00:03:04.900
was right when California
cuisine was just taking off.

00:03:04.900 --> 00:03:08.030
And I was actually working
upstairs in the cafe.

00:03:08.030 --> 00:03:09.960
And nobody knew at the
time what radicchio

00:03:09.960 --> 00:03:11.435
was, what goat cheese was.

00:03:11.435 --> 00:03:14.400
And people were coming
in and saying like oh,

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:15.597
is it like tofu?

00:03:15.597 --> 00:03:16.930
I was like no, it's goat cheese.

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:18.790
And they're like,
what's goat cheese?

00:03:18.790 --> 00:03:19.830
And people didn't know.

00:03:19.830 --> 00:03:21.589
And it's kind of funny
how it's evolved.

00:03:21.589 --> 00:03:24.172
People used to ask us how we got
the oranges red, because they

00:03:24.172 --> 00:03:25.950
were blood oranges.

00:03:25.950 --> 00:03:29.860
And it was kind of funny,
and it just kind of took off.

00:03:29.860 --> 00:03:31.835
And now radicchio
you take a flight,

00:03:31.835 --> 00:03:33.210
or you go to
Disneyland, and they

00:03:33.210 --> 00:03:34.900
have radicchio on the salad.

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:39.680
And I just had lunch here,
if Chez Panisse didn't exist,

00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:42.980
you guys would probably all be
eating Egg McMuffin sandwiches

00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:44.850
rather than all
the beautiful food.

00:03:44.850 --> 00:03:46.630
So I give Chez Panisse
a lot of credit,

00:03:46.630 --> 00:03:49.370
but it was a very
exciting time in America.

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:51.950
Also coincidentally,
with the rise of Google

00:03:51.950 --> 00:03:54.930
and technology, people being
much more aware of what they're

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:57.120
eating, what they're doing,
what they're thinking,

00:03:57.120 --> 00:03:57.995
what they're sharing.

00:03:57.995 --> 00:04:00.590
And that was also the
birth of food blogs.

00:04:00.590 --> 00:04:03.680
When we all, I
started in 1999 when

00:04:03.680 --> 00:04:06.240
the word "blog"
didn't even exist.

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:07.730
And people thought I was crazy.

00:04:07.730 --> 00:04:11.060
My friends who wrote
books thought I was crazy.

00:04:11.060 --> 00:04:14.059
But getting back to the original
question of Chez Panisse,

00:04:14.059 --> 00:04:15.600
it's actually been
really interesting

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:18.410
seeing how the Bay
Area once again,

00:04:18.410 --> 00:04:22.540
has been so innovative
in promoting food,

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:24.260
promoting technology.

00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:27.969
But we sort of tend to make
it really useful and relevant.

00:04:27.969 --> 00:04:30.260
So instead of just being this
movement and for the sake

00:04:30.260 --> 00:04:32.000
of having a food
movement, it was like no.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:33.208
This is about feeding people.

00:04:33.208 --> 00:04:35.240
This is about having farms.

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:37.820
I mean you think the idea of
having a farm outside of New

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:39.030
York City. is so crazy.

00:04:39.030 --> 00:04:41.430
But now it exists, and you
have this farmer's market

00:04:41.430 --> 00:04:42.970
with all local produce.

00:04:42.970 --> 00:04:46.500
And you go to Safeway and
they have local Straus Milk

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:47.330
and stuff.

00:04:47.330 --> 00:04:50.210
And that's all really
pretty radical still.

00:04:50.210 --> 00:04:51.690
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: Yeah.

00:04:51.690 --> 00:04:52.930
And recent.

00:04:52.930 --> 00:04:54.240
It works here in the Bay Area.

00:04:54.240 --> 00:04:56.375
We all kind of embrace it, but--

00:04:56.375 --> 00:04:56.900
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Who'd
have thought it?

00:04:56.900 --> 00:04:59.060
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: --it's
amazing how much it's spread,

00:04:59.060 --> 00:04:59.330
right?

00:04:59.330 --> 00:05:00.996
DAVID LEBOVITZ: I
never would've thought

00:05:00.996 --> 00:05:03.030
that I'd have kale in my teeth.

00:05:03.030 --> 00:05:06.250
I'm like-- we used to eat
iceberg lettuce salad.

00:05:06.250 --> 00:05:08.560
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: Just to
riff off that for a second,

00:05:08.560 --> 00:05:10.670
do you think California
and the Bay Area

00:05:10.670 --> 00:05:12.930
continues to be one
of the main places

00:05:12.930 --> 00:05:16.890
where food is sort of
innovated from like the quality

00:05:16.890 --> 00:05:18.750
of ingredients, and
freshness, and organic,

00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:19.595
and everything else?

00:05:19.595 --> 00:05:22.220
What do you see as you, I mean,
you get around the world a lot.

00:05:22.220 --> 00:05:22.600
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Right.

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:23.430
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
Do we have competition

00:05:23.430 --> 00:05:24.730
that we should be worried about?

00:05:24.730 --> 00:05:25.330
DAVID LEBOVITZ:
I don't think so.

00:05:25.330 --> 00:05:27.371
I think actually San
Francisco and the Bay Area's

00:05:27.371 --> 00:05:30.200
actually very conservative
in terms of food.

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:32.672
People don't like trends here.

00:05:32.672 --> 00:05:34.130
I'm not going to
mention any names,

00:05:34.130 --> 00:05:36.717
but there's been a lot of
molecular gastronomy stuff.

00:05:36.717 --> 00:05:38.550
And the people have
come through and they've

00:05:38.550 --> 00:05:41.620
sold out audiences in
theaters, and so forth.

00:05:41.620 --> 00:05:44.490
But nobody, if they had
opened restaurants here,

00:05:44.490 --> 00:05:45.800
nobody would have liked them.

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:49.680
Because people really appreciate
very simple, basic food.

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:51.130
Going through the
cafeteria here,

00:05:51.130 --> 00:05:53.750
everybody's eating
grilled asparagus.

00:05:53.750 --> 00:05:56.870
It's not fancy,
there's no foam on it,

00:05:56.870 --> 00:06:01.530
there's no, there's not turkey
and clam ice cream on the side.

00:06:01.530 --> 00:06:03.460
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: No
stir fried lamb brains,

00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:04.376
or anything like that.

00:06:04.376 --> 00:06:07.080
DAVID LEBOVITZ: It's a
very conservative food

00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:09.520
community here,
but in a good way.

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:11.972
And I think it's really,
like you go to Zuni,

00:06:11.972 --> 00:06:14.180
and you get a really good
hamburger or roast chicken.

00:06:14.180 --> 00:06:17.860
And you're making this face,
people think about that--

00:06:17.860 --> 00:06:17.980
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
Sorry, I love Zuni.

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:18.730
But you know that.

00:06:18.730 --> 00:06:19.530
That's where we go.

00:06:19.530 --> 00:06:20.110
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Yeah, you
think about that food,

00:06:20.110 --> 00:06:22.220
and you just go wow,
it's really good.

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:23.720
And it doesn't need to be fancy.

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:25.800
Just let the ingredients
speak for itself.

00:06:25.800 --> 00:06:27.290
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: It's one of
the reasons I love living here.

00:06:27.290 --> 00:06:29.980
DAVID LEBOVITZ: But quality
always speaks for itself.

00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:32.800
There's a lot of stuff out
there as everybody knows;

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:35.130
you work for search
engine company.

00:06:35.130 --> 00:06:36.464
The good stuff rises to the top.

00:06:36.464 --> 00:06:38.754
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: Well,
that's why Alice can get away

00:06:38.754 --> 00:06:41.617
with serving a bowl of fruit as
her main dessert course, right?

00:06:41.617 --> 00:06:43.450
Some of the best fruit
that you'll ever eat,

00:06:43.450 --> 00:06:45.570
but completely undressed,
completely naked.

00:06:45.570 --> 00:06:48.340
What was it that,
what was your pivot?

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:51.290
What made you say well,
I'm an amazing pastry chef

00:06:51.290 --> 00:06:52.770
and I love doing
this, but damn it.

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:55.710
I want to write full time, and
I want to make this my career?

00:06:55.710 --> 00:06:56.950
DAVID LEBOVITZ: I turned 40.

00:06:56.950 --> 00:06:58.200
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: Ah, I see.

00:06:58.200 --> 00:06:59.540
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Restaurant
work is really hard.

00:06:59.540 --> 00:07:01.780
And during that whole
California cuisine movement,

00:07:01.780 --> 00:07:03.400
I guess it was the '80s, '90s.

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:04.700
Everybody wanted to be a chef.

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:06.180
And I still hear
that from people.

00:07:06.180 --> 00:07:08.720
When I worked in the kitchen
at Chez Panisse's, people

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:11.011
who are lawyers who used to
come in the kitchen and go,

00:07:11.011 --> 00:07:12.092
I would love to do this.

00:07:12.092 --> 00:07:13.550
And you're like,
do you really want

00:07:13.550 --> 00:07:15.440
to do this for minimum wage?

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:17.450
And do you really want
to peel apples all day?

00:07:17.450 --> 00:07:17.950
Yeah.

00:07:17.950 --> 00:07:22.430
Maybe have dinner parties and
subscribe to Martha Stewart,

00:07:22.430 --> 00:07:26.234
build a nice kitchen, and
we all live hand to mouth.

00:07:26.234 --> 00:07:28.650
So there was a lot of people
who are getting into cooking,

00:07:28.650 --> 00:07:31.660
myself included at the time,
we worked really, really hard.

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:33.330
Somebody recently
asked me on Twitter,

00:07:33.330 --> 00:07:35.084
how do I get to do what you do?

00:07:35.084 --> 00:07:37.000
I was like, you stand
at the back of a kitchen

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:38.780
and you roll dough for 30 years.

00:07:41.850 --> 00:07:44.310
But when I hit 40
I was like, what

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:47.720
am I going to do with
the rest of my life?

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:49.550
I couldn't stand up all day.

00:07:49.550 --> 00:07:51.160
I was just tired.

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:54.810
I was really, I'd done the
same thing over and over.

00:07:54.810 --> 00:07:57.030
And one thing, one
equality Americans

00:07:57.030 --> 00:07:59.640
have that I've learned
from living in Europe,

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:01.884
is we're really good at
reinventing ourselves.

00:08:01.884 --> 00:08:03.300
We're very good
at saying you know

00:08:03.300 --> 00:08:05.070
what, I'm tired of
being an architect.

00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:09.760
I want to open a cupcake shop,
or let's start a search engine,

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:11.390
I'm going to write a book.

00:08:11.390 --> 00:08:13.410
We do that, and we just
say I'm going to do it.

00:08:13.410 --> 00:08:14.770
And if it doesn't work, it's OK.

00:08:14.770 --> 00:08:17.080
But we're not
afraid to try stuff.

00:08:17.080 --> 00:08:18.670
So I just thought you know what?

00:08:18.670 --> 00:08:21.890
It's time to turn the Etch a
Sketch over, give it a shake,

00:08:21.890 --> 00:08:22.970
and start again.

00:08:22.970 --> 00:08:24.630
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
Is that what,

00:08:24.630 --> 00:08:27.510
was it sort of the break
in switching to writing

00:08:27.510 --> 00:08:31.620
and your pseudo midlife crisis
that sent you to Paris as well,

00:08:31.620 --> 00:08:34.169
or was it-- I mean, I know
you've always loved Paris.

00:08:34.169 --> 00:08:36.799
And I'm not surprised
that you live there now.

00:08:36.799 --> 00:08:38.761
What brought you to Paris then?

00:08:38.761 --> 00:08:40.260
DAVID LEBOVITZ: I
don't really know.

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:41.676
I didn't have
anything to do here.

00:08:41.676 --> 00:08:44.847
I'd lived in San Francisco
for 20 something years.

00:08:44.847 --> 00:08:45.930
I was like, you know what?

00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:47.740
I want to go somewhere else.

00:08:47.740 --> 00:08:51.490
And I thought, well Paris--
I was never a francophile.

00:08:51.490 --> 00:08:54.760
I wasn't like oh my God, my
dream is to live in Paris.

00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:56.010
Audrey Hepburn.

00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:59.321
I just wanted to go, I thought
it'd be an interesting place.

00:08:59.321 --> 00:08:59.820
And it was.

00:08:59.820 --> 00:09:01.650
It's a really good
place to write,

00:09:01.650 --> 00:09:04.570
because nobody bothers you.

00:09:04.570 --> 00:09:07.690
People, you can stay in your
apartment for weeks and months,

00:09:07.690 --> 00:09:09.080
and nobody thinks that's weird.

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:10.960
Cindy's laughing
because she lived there.

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:12.140
And it's true.

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:14.270
You could sit in
a cafe by yourself

00:09:14.270 --> 00:09:16.540
and you're not distracted.

00:09:16.540 --> 00:09:19.300
And also for me, I
developed as a writer there.

00:09:19.300 --> 00:09:21.097
Because everything
I do there, if I

00:09:21.097 --> 00:09:23.430
go out and get a loaf of
bread, if I open my front door,

00:09:23.430 --> 00:09:24.670
there's material.

00:09:24.670 --> 00:09:25.430
There's a story.

00:09:25.430 --> 00:09:28.480
Everything I do, buying
shoelaces, getting

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:31.110
yelled at, buying
cheese, whatever.

00:09:31.110 --> 00:09:32.130
Coming up with a recipe.

00:09:32.130 --> 00:09:34.470
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: You've
shared a lot of those stories--

00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:34.570
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Too much.

00:09:34.570 --> 00:09:36.320
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
--with me and my wife.

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:39.630
I don't know that they're
all appropriate for a work

00:09:39.630 --> 00:09:42.231
audience, but are there
a couple anecdotes

00:09:42.231 --> 00:09:43.980
that you can share
just to sort of comment

00:09:43.980 --> 00:09:47.942
on the quirkiness
of living in Paris?

00:09:47.942 --> 00:09:49.650
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Well,
it was interesting.

00:09:49.650 --> 00:09:51.090
I recently went
out to where they

00:09:51.090 --> 00:09:53.690
harvest the salt off
the Atlantic coast.

00:09:53.690 --> 00:09:56.160
And if you look
at a map of France

00:09:56.160 --> 00:09:59.010
from the air, Google Earth, you
can see all these salt marshes

00:09:59.010 --> 00:10:01.250
that have been around
since Roman times.

00:10:01.250 --> 00:10:04.630
And the people hand harvest
this salt, and it's amazing.

00:10:04.630 --> 00:10:07.170
You go to a store here
and you buy, and it's $12.

00:10:07.170 --> 00:10:08.250
And we went there.

00:10:08.250 --> 00:10:09.708
We spent a weekend
because I wanted

00:10:09.708 --> 00:10:11.380
to see the salt being harvested.

00:10:11.380 --> 00:10:14.390
And we're sitting in this
restaurant right on the coast.

00:10:14.390 --> 00:10:17.250
Beautiful salt marshes,
beautiful piles of salt

00:10:17.250 --> 00:10:18.470
that they'd all faked.

00:10:18.470 --> 00:10:21.260
And on the table
is industrial salt.

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:23.255
The worst salt in the world.

00:10:23.255 --> 00:10:25.505
And I said to the waitress
I said, it's kind of funny.

00:10:25.505 --> 00:10:27.762
It's right out, you have it.

00:10:27.762 --> 00:10:29.294
And they're like, oh.

00:10:29.294 --> 00:10:30.710
They just didn't
even notice that,

00:10:30.710 --> 00:10:34.090
because it didn't
even occur to them.

00:10:34.090 --> 00:10:37.850
So that kind of stuff, being
an outsider is actually funny.

00:10:37.850 --> 00:10:40.890
Because my partner's French,
and he's pretty funny.

00:10:40.890 --> 00:10:41.839
Have you met Roman?

00:10:41.839 --> 00:10:43.880
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: I've
heard a lot about Roman.

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:45.254
I don't think
we've ever met, no.

00:10:45.254 --> 00:10:48.820
DAVID LEBOVITZ: And so
I get motivated by him.

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:51.339
He thinks I'm funny
too, most of the time.

00:10:51.339 --> 00:10:53.380
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: That's
good, because you are.

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:54.790
The other one that
I'll throw out there,

00:10:54.790 --> 00:10:56.020
I don't know if David remembers.

00:10:56.020 --> 00:10:58.395
He'll remember the place that
we were eating at in Paris.

00:10:58.395 --> 00:11:01.160
But we get to, what was the
name of the restaurant, again?

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:02.535
DAVID LEBOVITZ:
The black plates.

00:11:02.535 --> 00:11:05.515
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: We're going
to the ketchup on lobster.

00:11:05.515 --> 00:11:06.390
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Yeah.

00:11:06.390 --> 00:11:09.790
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: So you're
going through an exquisite meal

00:11:09.790 --> 00:11:11.910
in Paris, and David
and I will have

00:11:11.910 --> 00:11:13.674
rack brains for the
name of the place.

00:11:13.674 --> 00:11:15.340
But it was one of the
places on the list

00:11:15.340 --> 00:11:17.150
that my wife knew that
she wanted to go to.

00:11:17.150 --> 00:11:18.691
And of course, you
meet up with David

00:11:18.691 --> 00:11:20.982
and you magically get
into these places.

00:11:20.982 --> 00:11:22.440
And we're working
through the meal.

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:27.355
Really elegant, fancy, high end,
three star sort of French food.

00:11:27.355 --> 00:11:28.730
And we get to the
lobster course.

00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:30.730
And everybody's excited
about the lobster course

00:11:30.730 --> 00:11:32.380
because the three
of us love lobster.

00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:34.270
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Lobster's
very expensive in France.

00:11:34.270 --> 00:11:34.670
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
That's right.

00:11:34.670 --> 00:11:36.520
And it can be really good.

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:38.110
I mean, the French
know how to cook

00:11:38.110 --> 00:11:40.730
lobster, which is
not overcook it.

00:11:40.730 --> 00:11:42.884
But then that lobster
was drenched in a,

00:11:42.884 --> 00:11:44.300
and how would we
say it in French?

00:11:44.300 --> 00:11:45.591
What was the name of the sauce?

00:11:45.591 --> 00:11:49.450
I it was straight up, it
read as, "cat soup sauce."

00:11:49.450 --> 00:11:51.550
And I'm like, what
the hell is this?

00:11:51.550 --> 00:11:53.260
And it was just
straight ketchup.

00:11:53.260 --> 00:11:56.177
And the waiter comes
out, and is really,

00:11:56.177 --> 00:11:58.510
really proud of the sauce
that they put on this lobster.

00:11:58.510 --> 00:12:00.870
Because it was ketchup
that was made specially

00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:02.712
by this friend of his,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:12:02.712 --> 00:12:04.920
And the three of us are
eating it trying to enjoy it.

00:12:04.920 --> 00:12:07.580
But again from an outsider
perspective just going, well

00:12:07.580 --> 00:12:08.080
shit.

00:12:08.080 --> 00:12:11.590
They just put ketchup
on my lobster.

00:12:11.590 --> 00:12:13.990
I don't know, just I
can imagine all kinds

00:12:13.990 --> 00:12:15.550
of fascinating
stories like that.

00:12:15.550 --> 00:12:16.840
Let's pivot a little
bit to the book.

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:18.450
I want to make sure
we give folks a chance

00:12:18.450 --> 00:12:19.530
to ask questions, as well.

00:12:19.530 --> 00:12:19.790
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Sure.

00:12:19.790 --> 00:12:21.248
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
This is, you've

00:12:21.248 --> 00:12:22.590
written a whole bunch of books.

00:12:22.590 --> 00:12:25.930
You've largely focused more
specifically on cookbooks.

00:12:25.930 --> 00:12:27.450
Now, you're taking
a pivot to more

00:12:27.450 --> 00:12:30.940
of what I would kind of deem
a memoir cross cookbook.

00:12:30.940 --> 00:12:34.500
What was it the sort of
motivated you to do that?

00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:38.764
Why the bigger journey, the
more work, the, I don't know.

00:12:38.764 --> 00:12:40.180
DAVID LEBOVITZ:
More work is the--

00:12:40.180 --> 00:12:40.760
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
Yeah, you just

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:41.800
wanted to do the more work?

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:42.440
DAVID LEBOVITZ:
Do the harder way.

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:43.856
Yeah, it's the
Chez Panisse thing.

00:12:43.856 --> 00:12:47.180
I always find the
harder way to do it.

00:12:47.180 --> 00:12:50.500
I'd written a memoir,
when I moved to Paris,

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:51.542
my blog kind of took off.

00:12:51.542 --> 00:12:53.083
And a lot of people
were saying well,

00:12:53.083 --> 00:12:54.820
you should write a
book about your story.

00:12:54.820 --> 00:12:57.320
So I wrote a book at the time,
which was very well received.

00:12:57.320 --> 00:13:00.200
And it was kind of funny,
and very young and fresh.

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:01.430
And we change.

00:13:01.430 --> 00:13:05.200
People look at my old recipes,
I had a chance to revise a book.

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:07.860
And I was like oh, I don't make
the brownies like that anymore.

00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:08.454
I do this now.

00:13:08.454 --> 00:13:10.620
And that changed, so that
changed, and that changed.

00:13:10.620 --> 00:13:12.520
My life has changed a lot.

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:14.145
So I'd proposed a
book to my publisher,

00:13:14.145 --> 00:13:17.370
who I love, Ten Speed Press.

00:13:17.370 --> 00:13:20.220
Just a book about France,
another book about stories.

00:13:20.220 --> 00:13:23.090
And the publisher,
Aaron, who's great,

00:13:23.090 --> 00:13:24.440
said it needs to have recipes.

00:13:24.440 --> 00:13:26.726
I was like [CRYING].

00:13:26.726 --> 00:13:29.100
And I'd spent eight months
working on the proposal, which

00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:31.820
is what you normally
do when writing a book.

00:13:31.820 --> 00:13:35.400
And he said well, we
need to have recipes.

00:13:35.400 --> 00:13:37.740
And to make a long story
short, I realized he was right.

00:13:37.740 --> 00:13:40.850
Because as a cook, my
story is through recipes.

00:13:40.850 --> 00:13:42.330
My story's through cooking.

00:13:42.330 --> 00:13:46.070
I cook all day, and
that's who I am.

00:13:46.070 --> 00:13:46.570
I'm a cook.

00:13:46.570 --> 00:13:48.970
I've been a cook since
I was 16 professionally.

00:13:48.970 --> 00:13:52.650
Well, I was a dishwasher in a
restaurant-- dishwasher bonanza

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:56.910
sirloin pit, and
then the guys who

00:13:56.910 --> 00:14:00.540
tended the meat in the naugahyde
aprons used to terrorize me

00:14:00.540 --> 00:14:03.330
with the flaming
stakes and stuff.

00:14:03.330 --> 00:14:05.369
We're going to throw
you on the fire.

00:14:05.369 --> 00:14:06.910
And now I'm like,
where are they now?

00:14:06.910 --> 00:14:09.098
I'm in Google.

00:14:09.098 --> 00:14:12.204
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
Come, join me.

00:14:12.204 --> 00:14:13.870
Last question that
I'll ask, and then we

00:14:13.870 --> 00:14:17.200
should turn it over to
friends in the audience.

00:14:17.200 --> 00:14:19.170
I've heard that you
had an opportunity

00:14:19.170 --> 00:14:20.080
to redo your kitchen.

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:23.297
I know your kitchen for
your already small Parisian

00:14:23.297 --> 00:14:24.505
apartment was not very large.

00:14:24.505 --> 00:14:25.422
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Right.

00:14:25.422 --> 00:14:26.796
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
I don't know.

00:14:26.796 --> 00:14:29.020
Talk to us a little bit
about the kitchen remodel.

00:14:29.020 --> 00:14:31.802
What you did, what
you're happy about.

00:14:31.802 --> 00:14:33.510
DAVID LEBOVITZ: OK,
well the short answer

00:14:33.510 --> 00:14:36.280
is when I started the remodeling
project, a friend of mine

00:14:36.280 --> 00:14:37.988
in Paris said, promise
me you won't write

00:14:37.988 --> 00:14:39.680
a book about
remodeling in France.

00:14:39.680 --> 00:14:40.360
I said, OK.

00:14:40.360 --> 00:14:43.624
And then that all the stuff
happened, and it was pretty,

00:14:43.624 --> 00:14:44.540
it was very difficult.

00:14:44.540 --> 00:14:46.123
I was working on the
book at the time,

00:14:46.123 --> 00:14:49.045
and actually if anyone here has
ever bought a house in America,

00:14:49.045 --> 00:14:50.950
it takes 30 days.

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:55.410
And France takes about
a year, just to close.

00:14:55.410 --> 00:14:59.620
It's really stressful, and
it's all very difficult.

00:14:59.620 --> 00:15:01.800
And then it needed
to be remodeled.

00:15:01.800 --> 00:15:04.094
And I thought, I've
done remodeling here.

00:15:04.094 --> 00:15:05.760
I'm like well, let's
just put this here,

00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:07.790
and this here, I want
a nice big kitchen.

00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:11.340
And to condense
the story, people

00:15:11.340 --> 00:15:13.340
were walking by
like on the street.

00:15:13.340 --> 00:15:14.050
They were looking
and they were like,

00:15:14.050 --> 00:15:15.320
are you building
a restaurant here?

00:15:15.320 --> 00:15:16.075
I'm like oh, that's the kitchen.

00:15:16.075 --> 00:15:17.710
They're like--
because I have a big,

00:15:17.710 --> 00:15:20.037
I was like I want a
big area to cook in.

00:15:20.037 --> 00:15:21.870
Traditionally actually,
French people always

00:15:21.870 --> 00:15:24.910
had the kitchen apart
from their apartments.

00:15:24.910 --> 00:15:27.570
You never wanted, I mean
going back in history,

00:15:27.570 --> 00:15:29.940
the maid always made the food.

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:32.230
Like you didn't, it's
very class orient--

00:15:32.230 --> 00:15:34.920
you didn't want to be
around the smell of food.

00:15:34.920 --> 00:15:37.260
So they have this,
the new concept is,

00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:40.590
they call it cuisine American,
or an American kitchen.

00:15:40.590 --> 00:15:43.270
Which is open with a big counter
and everybody likes that,

00:15:43.270 --> 00:15:45.210
and you see the
stools and stuff.

00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:47.670
But it was very challenging.

00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:49.990
A lot of stuff,
you're tech people.

00:15:49.990 --> 00:15:52.020
I said, I want USB ports.

00:15:52.020 --> 00:15:53.522
We're doing the electricity.

00:15:53.522 --> 00:15:54.980
So I came home one
day, and there's

00:15:54.980 --> 00:15:56.640
these cords hanging
out of the wall.

00:15:56.640 --> 00:15:58.720
It was like the wrong way.

00:15:58.720 --> 00:16:01.460
So I was like-- I was like, no.

00:16:01.460 --> 00:16:04.690
I need to plug my stuff into
the wall, not my apartment

00:16:04.690 --> 00:16:06.960
into my computer.

00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:10.680
So we had a two week
argument about that.

00:16:10.680 --> 00:16:14.230
And there's a story in the book
about how the new contractor

00:16:14.230 --> 00:16:15.850
saved my life,
because I found out

00:16:15.850 --> 00:16:19.850
there was CO2 gas being
pumped into my apartment.

00:16:19.850 --> 00:16:23.068
And I was wondering why
was sleeping so well.

00:16:23.068 --> 00:16:26.500
I was like, I've been
sleeping really well lately.

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:27.811
12, 24 hours.

00:16:27.811 --> 00:16:30.310
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: Well, that's
the trick to sleeping well.

00:16:30.310 --> 00:16:31.280
Maybe I just need--

00:16:31.280 --> 00:16:33.457
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Well, I
don't recommend it, but--

00:16:33.457 --> 00:16:36.040
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: So why don't
we open up to everybody else?

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:38.960
My guess is lots of good
questions for David.

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:40.840
There's a mike floating around.

00:16:40.840 --> 00:16:42.483
Who has some good questions?

00:16:42.483 --> 00:16:44.316
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Or even
regular [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:44.316 --> 00:16:45.230
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: OK.

00:16:45.230 --> 00:16:46.340
DAVID LEBOVITZ: If you have any
questions about the recipe--

00:16:46.340 --> 00:16:47.540
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: And if
you don't have questions,

00:16:47.540 --> 00:16:49.123
David's going to ask
how to get higher

00:16:49.123 --> 00:16:52.950
in the search results ranking,
how to drop his AdWords cost,

00:16:52.950 --> 00:16:55.830
why the street view
picture of his home--

00:16:55.830 --> 00:16:57.780
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Shows
the bathroom, shower.

00:17:01.679 --> 00:17:03.720
Everyone's always like,
that's not my department.

00:17:03.720 --> 00:17:05.909
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: M-hm.

00:17:05.909 --> 00:17:06.450
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:17:06.450 --> 00:17:07.176
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Hi.

00:17:07.176 --> 00:17:08.000
AUDIENCE: I'm a big fan.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.380
Thank you for all the
wonderful recipes on your blog,

00:17:10.380 --> 00:17:13.250
and beautiful photos on
your Instagram, and Google+,

00:17:13.250 --> 00:17:14.020
and everything.

00:17:14.020 --> 00:17:15.686
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Oh,
I'm a fan of Google.

00:17:15.686 --> 00:17:16.710
[INAUDIBLE] feedback.

00:17:16.710 --> 00:17:19.849
AUDIENCE: Really appreciate it.

00:17:19.849 --> 00:17:22.000
And you really made
my last trip to Paris

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.230
with all the recommendations
and things on your blog.

00:17:24.230 --> 00:17:26.650
If you were moving
back to San Francisco,

00:17:26.650 --> 00:17:28.290
what are some things
you would really

00:17:28.290 --> 00:17:31.400
take from your Paris experience
that would maybe transform

00:17:31.400 --> 00:17:33.529
the way you would
live here again?

00:17:33.529 --> 00:17:34.820
DAVID LEBOVITZ: The way I shop.

00:17:34.820 --> 00:17:38.040
I'm used to, I mean I walk
everywhere, and I shop.

00:17:38.040 --> 00:17:40.580
I go to the bakery everyday,
and I go to the cheese shop,

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:42.290
and I have people at the market.

00:17:42.290 --> 00:17:44.426
And here, it's so
easy to buy stuff.

00:17:44.426 --> 00:17:46.550
You go to the supermarket,
you drive up to a place,

00:17:46.550 --> 00:17:48.040
and you just buy everything.

00:17:48.040 --> 00:17:50.470
And I would still really
try to hold on to that,

00:17:50.470 --> 00:17:53.120
like getting my milk from
one place and cheese.

00:17:53.120 --> 00:17:54.960
And even though it
drives you crazy

00:17:54.960 --> 00:17:57.320
if you're trying to do a
cookbook, because you know.

00:17:57.320 --> 00:17:58.720
It's like, I need an orange.

00:17:58.720 --> 00:18:00.790
And the store's
closed until Monday,

00:18:00.790 --> 00:18:03.090
and you have to wait until
Tuesday because they don't

00:18:03.090 --> 00:18:04.610
have anyone to stock the store.

00:18:04.610 --> 00:18:06.980
And Cindy's laughing because
you remember this stuff.

00:18:06.980 --> 00:18:08.610
It's like OK.

00:18:08.610 --> 00:18:10.900
So just going more small scale.

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:13.791
And actually, eating everything.

00:18:13.791 --> 00:18:15.290
When I left the
restaurant business,

00:18:15.290 --> 00:18:17.100
I was a little chunky.

00:18:17.100 --> 00:18:21.770
And I was always a thin person,
and I made a conscious effort

00:18:21.770 --> 00:18:22.920
to lose a lot of weight.

00:18:22.920 --> 00:18:24.690
And I was trying
to eat egg whites,

00:18:24.690 --> 00:18:26.960
and not eat so much fat.

00:18:26.960 --> 00:18:28.810
In France, I eat everything.

00:18:28.810 --> 00:18:33.050
And I've kind of lost weight
until this trip right now.

00:18:33.050 --> 00:18:35.750
And I've just been eating
ribs and stuff, so.

00:18:35.750 --> 00:18:37.580
I probably wouldn't
eat all this stuff

00:18:37.580 --> 00:18:40.570
that I used to eat in
America like tacos,

00:18:40.570 --> 00:18:42.096
or burritos, and stuff.

00:18:42.096 --> 00:18:43.580
Does that makes sense?

00:18:43.580 --> 00:18:46.930
No lobster with ketchup.

00:18:46.930 --> 00:18:48.810
AUDIENCE: So it's a
two part question.

00:18:48.810 --> 00:18:51.000
As a technologist
and a home cook,

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.050
I always have this love hate
relationship with sort of tech,

00:18:54.050 --> 00:18:54.550
right?

00:18:54.550 --> 00:18:57.200
How much is going to be
useful in the kitchen?

00:18:57.200 --> 00:18:59.030
Most the time it's
useless to me,

00:18:59.030 --> 00:19:01.200
but-- so it's two part question.

00:19:01.200 --> 00:19:06.780
One is, what other kinds, if you
have any tech in your kitchen,

00:19:06.780 --> 00:19:07.670
what is it?

00:19:07.670 --> 00:19:11.420
And then the other
is if you don't, what

00:19:11.420 --> 00:19:14.484
would be great to have
that maybe doesn't exist?

00:19:14.484 --> 00:19:15.900
DAVID LEBOVITZ:
You know, I don't.

00:19:15.900 --> 00:19:19.070
Years before the iPad came
out, I did a story on my site

00:19:19.070 --> 00:19:20.030
about ecookbooks.

00:19:20.030 --> 00:19:22.310
Because there were some
devices that had recipes.

00:19:22.310 --> 00:19:25.630
I'm like, you know,
is this going to work?

00:19:25.630 --> 00:19:28.520
Are people going to want to
look at a tablet and cook?

00:19:28.520 --> 00:19:31.310
It even if you could
have Julia Child with you

00:19:31.310 --> 00:19:34.900
on this thing saying cut
up the chicken this way.

00:19:34.900 --> 00:19:38.090
And when I write recipes,
I write them all longhand.

00:19:38.090 --> 00:19:40.260
And even downstairs,
the test kitchen woman,

00:19:40.260 --> 00:19:42.140
she's still writing longhand.

00:19:42.140 --> 00:19:44.810
So I don't really have
any tech in my kitchen.

00:19:44.810 --> 00:19:48.100
I don't use a computer
when I'm typing recipes.

00:19:48.100 --> 00:19:50.990
That's in another room.

00:19:50.990 --> 00:19:54.370
What I would like is,
and I know this exists,

00:19:54.370 --> 00:19:56.630
but I'm just too crazy to do it.

00:19:56.630 --> 00:19:59.890
Is a voice activated
tool so I could

00:19:59.890 --> 00:20:05.000
say, chop one onion, so I didn't
have to stop and write it down.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:07.670
Or something that
would record what I do,

00:20:07.670 --> 00:20:10.797
and condense it so that I
could just have it right

00:20:10.797 --> 00:20:12.380
there without having
to go through all

00:20:12.380 --> 00:20:15.697
this recordings of stuff.

00:20:15.697 --> 00:20:16.530
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:20:16.530 --> 00:20:19.240
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
I can, is that sort

00:20:19.240 --> 00:20:20.240
of what you had in mind?

00:20:20.240 --> 00:20:22.364
Or would you broaden your
question as well to like,

00:20:22.364 --> 00:20:24.370
do you have a KitchenAid
mixer in your kitchen--

00:20:24.370 --> 00:20:27.496
AUDIENCE: No, it actually
wasn't about the gadgets.

00:20:27.496 --> 00:20:28.870
Well, there's a
school of thought

00:20:28.870 --> 00:20:31.391
that says you only need a
chef's knife and a paring knife,

00:20:31.391 --> 00:20:31.890
right?

00:20:31.890 --> 00:20:32.390
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Exactly.

00:20:32.390 --> 00:20:33.931
AUDIENCE: So I'm
more on that school.

00:20:33.931 --> 00:20:39.966
But you could broaden it to
OK, when you're not cooking,

00:20:39.966 --> 00:20:41.340
and you go online
to look and see

00:20:41.340 --> 00:20:43.180
what other people are doing.

00:20:43.180 --> 00:20:46.520
Maybe you're looking for a
recipe or online services--

00:20:46.520 --> 00:20:49.830
although just to your
point about dictation,

00:20:49.830 --> 00:20:51.160
we definitely have that.

00:20:51.160 --> 00:20:53.719
But it's not structured
for that use case.

00:20:53.719 --> 00:20:55.760
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Yeah, you
see these refrigerators

00:20:55.760 --> 00:20:57.134
that tell you when
you need milk.

00:20:57.134 --> 00:20:58.850
It's like, I don't need that.

00:20:58.850 --> 00:21:01.930
I can open the door.

00:21:01.930 --> 00:21:03.930
But I need a
computer to write on,

00:21:03.930 --> 00:21:06.460
I need a computer to
go search for a recipe,

00:21:06.460 --> 00:21:07.860
or search for a technique.

00:21:07.860 --> 00:21:10.480
So a lot of this innovation in
the kitchen this kind of silly.

00:21:10.480 --> 00:21:12.920
And this whole idea of a
chef's knife, a paring knife,

00:21:12.920 --> 00:21:14.900
and a pan is really great.

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:17.231
I've gone to people's
houses, I was actually

00:21:17.231 --> 00:21:18.230
somewhere the other day.

00:21:18.230 --> 00:21:19.990
And they had turkey deep fryer.

00:21:19.990 --> 00:21:22.880
It was a machine just
for deep frying turkey.

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:23.895
And--

00:21:23.895 --> 00:21:25.895
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: That's
highly useful, right?

00:21:25.895 --> 00:21:29.540
DAVID LEBOVITZ: It's highly
useful one day of the year.

00:21:29.540 --> 00:21:32.220
It's people who have these very
big kitchens, and so forth.

00:21:32.220 --> 00:21:34.830
And I lived in a really, I
had a really nice kitchen

00:21:34.830 --> 00:21:36.230
here in San Francisco.

00:21:36.230 --> 00:21:38.230
And then I moved to a
very small place in Paris.

00:21:38.230 --> 00:21:39.604
I didn't have a
mixer for a year,

00:21:39.604 --> 00:21:40.820
and I just had a couple pans.

00:21:40.820 --> 00:21:41.930
And I wrote two books there.

00:21:41.930 --> 00:21:43.513
And it was good,
because I could write

00:21:43.513 --> 00:21:47.700
to people who have
small kitchens.

00:21:47.700 --> 00:21:49.920
Light up your wok
burner, and heat up

00:21:49.920 --> 00:21:53.260
six gallons of rice
bran oil, and then

00:21:53.260 --> 00:21:56.560
fry the quail hearts until, and
you're just-- all those kind

00:21:56.560 --> 00:21:58.210
of books kind of freak me out.

00:21:58.210 --> 00:22:00.570
Because I love when people
come to me and they go,

00:22:00.570 --> 00:22:02.210
I made your recipe
for madelines.

00:22:02.210 --> 00:22:03.290
They were great.

00:22:03.290 --> 00:22:04.610
I made your vanilla ice
cream, it was great.

00:22:04.610 --> 00:22:05.901
And that's what it's all about.

00:22:05.901 --> 00:22:08.990
And I think in spite of
how great technology is,

00:22:08.990 --> 00:22:13.640
it's just not, cooking
is a visceral experience.

00:22:13.640 --> 00:22:16.924
That's why books, I
wrote this book because,

00:22:16.924 --> 00:22:18.590
if you need a recipe
for chocolate cake,

00:22:18.590 --> 00:22:19.952
you can go online and find one.

00:22:19.952 --> 00:22:21.660
I wrote this book
because I wanted people

00:22:21.660 --> 00:22:24.590
to read about my life,
read about the recipes,

00:22:24.590 --> 00:22:26.950
and pick it up, and
touch it, and feel it.

00:22:26.950 --> 00:22:30.100
I chose the photographer,
because he's very,

00:22:30.100 --> 00:22:34.070
he's good at getting the sort
of the textures of vegetables,

00:22:34.070 --> 00:22:36.160
and meat, and Paris.

00:22:36.160 --> 00:22:38.770
Paris is not necessarily
a beautiful place.

00:22:38.770 --> 00:22:41.750
It is, but there's a
lot of funkiness to it,

00:22:41.750 --> 00:22:43.569
like the ethnic neighborhoods.

00:22:43.569 --> 00:22:45.860
I live near Belleville, which
is an Asian neighborhood.

00:22:45.860 --> 00:22:47.734
And people are like,
there's Asians in Paris?

00:22:47.734 --> 00:22:50.270
I'm like yeah, there's
a huge neighborhood.

00:22:50.270 --> 00:22:51.530
There's Indian neighborhoods.

00:22:51.530 --> 00:22:55.687
And I thought those short of
showed the diversity of Paris,

00:22:55.687 --> 00:22:57.270
and I wanted to show
that in the book.

