00:23:40.688 --> 00:23:41.482
DAVID LEBOVITZ: OK.

00:23:41.482 --> 00:23:42.440
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: OK.

00:23:42.440 --> 00:23:45.140
AUDIENCE: The other thing
is that I had a question

00:23:45.140 --> 00:23:49.330
for you is, how do you
balance that with Google, you

00:23:49.330 --> 00:23:52.730
can find like you said,
chocolate ginger cake

00:23:52.730 --> 00:23:53.670
recipe, right?

00:23:53.670 --> 00:23:56.550
Which is one of those I
imagine, yours is amazing.

00:23:56.550 --> 00:24:02.270
But you can search for a
million of those recipes.

00:24:02.270 --> 00:24:05.990
So how do you differentiate
yours with all the other ones?

00:24:05.990 --> 00:24:09.830
How do you balance making
it special enough, but not

00:24:09.830 --> 00:24:13.070
so esoteric that
normal people will,

00:24:13.070 --> 00:24:14.700
oh, that's way too many steps.

00:24:14.700 --> 00:24:17.350
That's way too many ingredients,
that's way too weird.

00:24:17.350 --> 00:24:19.349
So how do you balance that?

00:24:19.349 --> 00:24:21.140
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Well
the way I've actually,

00:24:21.140 --> 00:24:22.649
and this probably
sounds terrible,

00:24:22.649 --> 00:24:24.690
and you can turn the
cameras off when I say this,

00:24:24.690 --> 00:24:29.300
but I'm seeing a stratification
now on the internet.

00:24:29.300 --> 00:24:30.380
There's so much content.

00:24:30.380 --> 00:24:32.940
If you want that ginger
cake, you type ginger cake.

00:24:32.940 --> 00:24:34.760
But whose recipe is it?

00:24:34.760 --> 00:24:35.990
Who's written this recipe?

00:24:35.990 --> 00:24:37.530
If you go on a site
like Epicurious,

00:24:37.530 --> 00:24:39.110
they have a test kitchen.

00:24:39.110 --> 00:24:41.120
And the recipe works,
there's someone behind it.

00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:43.550
If people go to my
site, I test the recipe.

00:24:43.550 --> 00:24:45.560
I test them two or three times.

00:24:45.560 --> 00:24:47.770
For the book, at least
three times, if not more.

00:24:47.770 --> 00:24:51.500
And then Cindy gets the
recipe and goes over them.

00:24:51.500 --> 00:24:53.140
I vet the stuff.

00:24:53.140 --> 00:24:55.360
People want curated,
vetted content.

00:24:55.360 --> 00:24:58.940
There's so much stuff out
there that's not good.

00:24:58.940 --> 00:25:01.490
I want my name to be, I've
become a trusted name.

00:25:01.490 --> 00:25:05.190
I didn't do it intentionally,
but I have that chops.

00:25:05.190 --> 00:25:07.270
Because I'm a cookbook
writer, as well.

00:25:07.270 --> 00:25:10.270
So you can turn the
camera back on again now.

00:25:10.270 --> 00:25:12.390
But I actually try to cook
for a global audience.

00:25:12.390 --> 00:25:15.910
A third of my readers on my
site are from outside the US.

00:25:15.910 --> 00:25:19.430
So I'm very conscious of
if I call for a recipe,

00:25:19.430 --> 00:25:22.740
I write in grams,
if I use molasses,

00:25:22.740 --> 00:25:25.080
people are going to
say, what's molasses?

00:25:25.080 --> 00:25:27.060
And I'm very conscious of that.

00:25:27.060 --> 00:25:30.670
And that sort of endeared
me to a larger audience.

00:25:30.670 --> 00:25:34.450
Americans, we tend to be
enclosed in our country.

00:25:34.450 --> 00:25:36.740
And even though
Google's international,

00:25:36.740 --> 00:25:39.900
the internet makes us, we still
work within our own parameters.

00:25:39.900 --> 00:25:44.310
And I'm always constantly
trying to enforce this idea,

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:46.834
suggest this idea,
that we need to think

00:25:46.834 --> 00:25:48.000
about the rest of the world.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:52.510
How people in England cook,
what they use, and so forth.

00:25:52.510 --> 00:25:55.510
Does that answer
the second question?

00:25:55.510 --> 00:25:57.140
AUDIENCE: Sort of.

00:25:57.140 --> 00:25:59.200
