of recipes where

00:25:59.200 --> 00:26:02.834
they use very hard
to find ingredients.

00:26:02.834 --> 00:26:04.000
DAVID LEBOVITZ: I actually--

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:06.470
AUDIENCE: Especially
living in France, you know?

00:26:06.470 --> 00:26:08.470
DAVID LEBOVITZ: I actually
don't use ingredients

00:26:08.470 --> 00:26:09.761
that people can't get anywhere.

00:26:09.761 --> 00:26:11.280
I search a lot on the line.

00:26:11.280 --> 00:26:14.285
I always make sure that
anything in the book is,

00:26:14.285 --> 00:26:16.160
and actually, I try to
make sure everything's

00:26:16.160 --> 00:26:17.917
available in the community.

00:26:17.917 --> 00:26:20.000
There's nothing more
annoying than making a recipe

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.850
and go, oh, I have to
mail away for the spice.

00:26:22.850 --> 00:26:27.450
I do ask Cindy, I've written
butchers or called butchers,

00:26:27.450 --> 00:26:29.620
or emailed, I guess, in Texas.

00:26:29.620 --> 00:26:32.675
I'm like when you get a
ham hock, is it smoked?

00:26:32.675 --> 00:26:34.390
Can you get on
unsmoked hem hocks?

00:26:34.390 --> 00:26:35.510
So they're like, yes.

00:26:35.510 --> 00:26:37.390
But things like
sausages, I really want,

00:26:37.390 --> 00:26:39.050
and I give suggestions.

00:26:39.050 --> 00:26:40.810
For example, I have
a cassoulet recipe.

00:26:40.810 --> 00:26:42.290
And everybody's
like cassoulet has

00:26:42.290 --> 00:26:43.840
to be made with these beans.

00:26:43.840 --> 00:26:46.150
And they're these
haricot tarbais beans.

00:26:46.150 --> 00:26:50.650
And in America, they're
probably $30, $35 a pound.

00:26:50.650 --> 00:26:53.210
And it's hard to do a
recipe to tell somebody, buy

00:26:53.210 --> 00:26:55.790
two pounds of these beans.

00:26:55.790 --> 00:26:58.030
Because it's annoying,
and it's a peasant dishes.

00:26:58.030 --> 00:27:01.160
It's not, the esprit
or the soul of the dish

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:05.040
is to something that
anybody can make with,

00:27:05.040 --> 00:27:06.340
that's what French cuisine is.

00:27:06.340 --> 00:27:08.570
It's regional food
too, what's available.

00:27:08.570 --> 00:27:11.340
So I try to encourage people
to use what's available.

00:27:11.340 --> 00:27:13.620
And there's only one
ingredient in the book which

00:27:13.620 --> 00:27:16.260
is salt cod, which
I love a lot, which

00:27:16.260 --> 00:27:18.070
you might have to send away for.

00:27:18.070 --> 00:27:20.230
But other than that,
everything else is,

00:27:20.230 --> 00:27:24.370
I really strive to make
stuff that people can make.

00:27:24.370 --> 00:27:26.400
I've seen a lot of
chef's books with the 1/4

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:30.480
cup of squab stock, and
this-- I'm like, OK.

00:27:30.480 --> 00:27:31.534
They're just showing off.

00:27:31.534 --> 00:27:33.200
Or that's how they
cook in a restaurant,

00:27:33.200 --> 00:27:36.764
but that's not how
people cook, I think.

00:27:36.764 --> 00:27:37.930
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: It's OK.

00:27:37.930 --> 00:27:40.430
Here in the Bay Area, salt
cod is kind of the same thing

00:27:40.430 --> 00:27:41.430
as on endive these days.

00:27:41.430 --> 00:27:42.040
So like--

00:27:42.040 --> 00:27:43.910
DAVID LEBOVITZ: They couldn't
get it at Camino yesterday.

00:27:43.910 --> 00:27:44.170
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: Really?

00:27:44.170 --> 00:27:44.450
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Yeah.

00:27:44.450 --> 00:27:45.260
JONATHAN ALFERNESS: Oh, strange.

00:27:45.260 --> 00:27:45.725
DAVID LEBOVITZ: Yeah.

00:27:45.725 --> 00:27:47.308
JONATHAN ALFERNESS:
See it everywhere.

